%%%
# Poisson GLM with named link and predictor functions

The linear predictor and the inverse log-link are written as **function
definitions** (spec §05 "Function definition syntax") — sugar for lambdas.
Being first-class `functionof` values, they are used in higher-order
position: `predict` is broadcast over the covariate array with `broadcast`,
and the inverse-link `rate` is applied elementwise via dot-call (`rate.(…)`).

For each observation $i$:

$$\eta_i = a + b\,x_i,\qquad \mu_i = \exp(\eta_i),\qquad y_i \sim \mathrm{Poisson}(\mu_i).$$
%%%

x_data = [-1.0, 0.2, 0.5, 1.3, 2.1]
y_data = [0, 1, 2, 3, 8]

# --- Priors on the GLM coefficients ---
intercept ~ Normal(0.0, 1.0)
slope     ~ Normal(0.0, 1.0)

prior = lawof(record(intercept = intercept, slope = slope))

# --- Named linear predictor and inverse log-link (spec §05) ---
predict(a, b, x) = a + b * x
rate(eta)        = exp(eta)

# `predict` is a first-class function broadcast over the covariate array;
# `rate` is applied elementwise via dot-call.
eta = broadcast(predict, a = intercept, b = slope, x = x_data)
mu  = rate.(eta)

y ~ Poisson.(mu)

forward_kernel = kernelof(record(y = y), intercept = intercept, slope = slope)
L = likelihoodof(forward_kernel, record(y = y_data))
posterior = bayesupdate(L, prior)
